# State effect threads through runState on JS (js-effect-runner-preamble)

Regression for the JS effect-runner gap: `State.get/set/modify` were absent from
the JsGen effect-analysis builtin seed, so a `def counter(): Int ! State[Int]` using
only State was NOT recognised as effectful and got emitted as a PLAIN (non-CPS)
function — `State.get()` returned the raw Perform object and `State.set` ran eagerly
and was discarded, so `runState` reported the initial state (`(0, 0)` instead of
`(1, 0)`). Also the runner returned a bare JS array (rendered `List(…)`) rather than a
tuple. Both are fixed: State ops are in the builtin seed (CPS-lowered) and the runner
marks its `(state, result)` return as a tuple.

```scalascript
def counter(): Int ! State[Int] =
  val n = State.get()
  State.set(n + 1)
  n

val (finalState, value) = runState(0) { counter() }
println(value)
println(finalState)
println(runState(10) { counter() })
```
